# 5. 小さな灯り

Ichika: (What color should I make my next one...?)
Ichika: (The one I made for Saki has a cheerful color and fragrance to it... Shiho's is next, so maybe something more subdued would work best.)
Ichika: (As for Honami... Hmm... I could just ask her what she'd like since she's right here... But I'd rather give one to her without doing that.)
Ichika: (I have a feeling that she'll enjoy it more if I keep it a surprise.)
Honami: Oh, that reminds me. We can also make ones with flowers in them once you think you've gotten the hang of things.
Kanade: Oh, that's right. You bought some dried flowers earlier...
Honami: Yes, they're called botanical candles. And there's no need to worry since they're also fairly easy to make.
Honami: First, once we have finished scented candles like the ones we just made, we'll place them in a slightly larger mold.
Honami: That adds some space in between the candle and the mold, which you can fill with whatever flowers you like. After that, you'll pour in more wax...
Honami: And it'll be done once it hardens.
Kanade: Oh, is that how they made all those pretty candles at the store...?
Nene: It definitely seems much more doable after hearing how you can make them.
Ichika: (It sounds a little more difficult to make compared to a regular scented candle, but I'd like to give it a try...)
Ichika: (Oh, while I'm at it, I should make candles with flowers that represent Saki, Shiho, Honami, Miku and the others...)
Ichika: (Saki would be... Mimosas...? Statices could work for Shiho since they have this quiet and kind feel to them.)
Ichika: (What should I do for Honami, Miku and the others...?)
Kanade: You seem to be really enjoying this, Hoshino...
Ichika: Huh? R-Really?
Kanade: Yes, you seemed very happy just now. May I ask what you were thinking about?
Ichika: Oh, um... I was thinking about everyone who'd be receiving my candles, as well as which colors and flowers would suit them best...
Kanade: Oh, I've been thinking about that too. I've been trying to figure out which colors and fragrances would match them best...
Nene: Yeah, me too... I can't really make them like the ones they had in the store, but I'd like to make candles that put smiles on all their faces.
Ichika: You two were thinking about the same thing...? Is it normal for people to give their gifts this much thought when they're making them by hand...?
Kanade: Hehe. I wouldn't be surprised.
Ichika: (Oh, right...)
Ichika: (Honami always brings snacks and treats for us during practice...)
Ichika: (Which means she's probably thinking about us when making them.)
Ichika: Honami... I'm really glad that I decided to make these myself today.
Honami: What?
Ichika: I mean... You've helped me understand how wonderful and important it is to think about who'll be receiving a gift while making it...
Ichika: I finally understand how much thought goes into anything that's homemade.
Ichika: So, Honami, thank you... I really appreciate you being our teacher today and everything you've made for us up until this point.
Honami: Ichika...
Ichika: Wait, um...! I always appreciate it when you do make something for us! It's just... Making something myself like this has given me a better understanding of what goes through your mind...
Ichika: Imagining is one thing, but you really can gain a lot when you learn by doing.
Honami: Hehe. You may be right...
Ichika: Oh, the wax has already hardened... These are the last ones we made, so...
Kanade: So... That's all of them.
Honami: Nice work, everyone! I was very impressed towards the end since you all were able to make them on your own...!
Kanade: No, Ms. Mochizuki, we couldn't have done this without you. Thank you very much for teaching us how to make these...
Honami: Oh... Hehe. You're very welcome.
Nene: ...
Ichika: Is something the matter, Kusanagi...?
Nene: Huh? Oh, um... It's nothing serious, but...
Nene: It's just... We didn't make any candles for each other.
Ichika: Oh, you're right... I didn't make any for you...
Kanade: Me neither...
Kanade: However, while we're here, I'd like to make some scented candles for all of you.
Honami: Then, why don't we finish by each making one last candle...?
Kanade: Just one?
Honami: Yes, since making some for all of us right now would be very difficult...
Honami: Instead, let's each make one and pass them around as gifts to one another. How does that sound...?
Ichika: Yeah, okay...! Nice idea. I'd like to try that. Kusanagi, Kanade, what do you two think?
Honami: Hehe. Then, let's keep making more scented candles for a little bit longer.
Nene: They all seem to have hardened...
Kanade: Yes, I just checked by touching mine... I think they're ready.
Ichika: Then, let's remove them from the molds... Okay, they seem good.
Ichika: Oh, that reminds me... How do you want to gift these to each other? Should we wrap them first?
Nene: We don't have enough bags for the people here... So, how about we just give them to each other as is...?
Ichika: That seems a little odd if I'm going to be honest, but I guess we don't have much of a choice...
Honami: Hehe. I actually like that idea. You don't get many opportunities to give someone a gift right after you finish making it.
Nene: True. Then, um... Mine will go to you, Hoshino. You'll give yours to Yoisaki, and...
Kanade: I'll give mine to Ms. Mochizuki, and she'll give hers to you, Kusanagi.
Honami: Okay... I know it's a little early, but Happy Valentine's Day!
Nene: Here you are, Hoshino!
Ichika: Thank you! Oh, it already smells really nice. I'd like to light it as soon as I can.
Kanade: Happy Valentine's Day, Ms. Mochizuki. I really appreciate all the cleaning and cooking you do. I've been able to live with more ease thanks to you.
Honami: Hehe. Thank you very much. I also really enjoy working at your house, Ms. Yoisaki.
Nene: Exchanging gifts like this is making me feel all warm and fuzzy inside...
Ichika: Hehe. Me too. And as much as I want this to last, I'm really looking forward to using it...
Kanade: Oh, then... Why don't we light it now?
Ichika: Wait, now? Are you sure...?
Honami: Hehe. I see no problem with that.
Ichika: Okay... Then, Kusanagi, could I try lighting the candle you gave me?
Nene: O-Okay... I hope it works...
Kanade: Alright, let's light it.
Honami: Oh, wait. It'll look prettier if it's dark, so I'll turn off the lights.
Ichika: Thanks. Then, here we go...
Ichika: Oh wow...!
Ichika: I like how the little flame gently dances in the darkness...
Nene: Yeah, I'm starting to see why looking at them can help you relax...
Kanade: And this fragrance... It's so soothing.
Ichika: Yes, it is. It's gentle like...lavender...?
Ichika: (There's no way for me to tell what Kusanagi was thinking when she chose this fragrance, but...)
Ichika: It smells so nice...
Honami: Hehe... Looking at it in the darkness like this gives it such a mystical feel.
Ichika: Yeah... I didn't realize that a candle's flame could be so beautiful.
Nene: I'm a little moved by it too... Especially since I made it myself.
Ichika: Yeah... Thank you for making me such a beautiful scented candle, Kusanagi.
Ichika: It's hard for me to put into words... But it's like I can feel your kindness emanating from it.
Nene: S-Stop, that's really embarrassing... Still, I'm glad you like it so much.
Nene: Um... To be honest... I was pretty nervous throughout the day...
Kanade: Oh, you were?
Nene: Y-Yes. I hadn't spoken to Mochizuki in a long time, and I didn't know anything about you, Yoisaki...
Nene: So, I was worried that I wouldn't be able to keep any conversations going with either of you.
Nene: But you two are so nice that I felt completely fine before I realized it...
Nene: So, thank you for today... I feel good about doing this because of you.
Kanade: I'm also glad that I got to meet you today, Kusanagi...
Honami: I feel the same way. I hope we get another chance to do something like this together.
Honami: Anyway, let's finish by blowing out the flames on the candle.
Kanade: All together?
Honami: Yes. We can blow on it at the same time.
Ichika: Wait, why...? Oh, actually... That could be fun. It'd be like a birthday party.
Nene: Hehe. You're right. Then, shall we?
Honami: Okay... Ready? One, two...
